@node "Description" "HTTPJ v2.00 - Description"

   In these hindmost years @{b}InterNet@{ub} has become the true fashion of the informatic: to the mother of all the nets, in fact, are added each day new users, inclined by ludicious purposes or job necessities. Users has discovered how it is possible to obtain each kind of information, in real time, at a simple phone call cost (when necessary). Each firm by now has its HTML pages where publicizes its own products and establishes a direct thread with the costumers. The word "@{b}NetSurfer@{ub}" has been created, indicating who likes travelling with the help of a browser between the thousands of WWW existing pages on the net.

   @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} is a program born to receive HTML pages sending commands directly from shell and now it's capable to automatically get whole directory trees from remote servers.  Its features are listed below:

 ·  It fully supports @{b}HTTP 1.0@{ub} and @b{b}HTML 3.2@{ub} and some special extensions used by Netscape and Internet Explorer. It also allows anonymous navigation.

 ·  Fully managed from shell, it doesn't need external configuration file, so it's easy of use.

 ·  It allows reception of a single document, a document with images or an entire tree (Mirror); document links are modified for a correct navigation.

 ·  Management of @{b}Local Mirrors@{ub} (links are refered to destination path) and @{b}Real Mirrors@{ub} (links are refered to destination site) with the option to specify maximum depth level for local tree and other hosts.

 ·  Full support for @{b}Proxy Server@{ub} with the option to disable the cache.

 ·  Thanks to the @{b}UPDATE@{ub} option it doesn't load documents unmodified since the last download.

 ·  If the requested document has been moved, the program will automatically request for the new address.

 ·  The code has been rewritten suing all the Commodore directives:  it is stable and doesn't cause Enforcer Hit.  As it's written in C language it's very fast.

 ·  It requires very little memory: other than the one used by the program itself, it's allocated only the receiving buffer (configurable and set by default to 5 Kb) and the possible HTML document current loading (@{b}except for@{ub} images and archives).


Let's see now a few possible utilization of HTTPJ:

 ·  Using a predisposed script, it is possible to download the last world news page from the net, convert it in ASCII format and display it with a normal text viewer.

 ·  BBS SysOps could have on line the pages with the timetable of the trains, airplanes, undergrounds, always up-to-date.

 ·  With the help of a script, it is possible to teach our mailer to download a file announced in a message, directly from its support site.

 ·  Equally, the tonight television programs list could be obtained.

 ·  Internet Providers could manage the mirror of much consulted pages by their users.

 ·  Users which find an HTML online manual can download it and read it locally, offline, with a browser.


   Only the imagination could limit the use of this program, chiefly useful for Sysops that want to supply their users always up-to-date news.

@EndNode

@node "Distribution" "HTTPJ v2.00 - Distribution"

   @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} program is © 1996 by Piergiorgio Ghezzo.

   It is distributed as @{b}Freeware@{ub}: no registration needed, the archive that contains the program can be freely distributed, provided that it won't be modified and a remuneration for the copy won't be required. Insertion of the archive inside PD program collections (for example inside Aminet CDs or disks enclosed with magazines) is allowed, provided that the author is informed.

   @{b}THE AUTHOR IS NOT LIABLE FOR PROBLEMS DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY CAUSED BY ITS PROGRAM.@{ub} The original archive is virus-free guaranteed.

@EndNode

@node "Requirements" "HTTPJ v2.00 - Requirements"

   @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} works on @{b}Amiga@{ub} with any processor and KickStart 2.0 or above; memory requirement is insignificant and it depends on (configurable) transmission buffer size.

   In order to download documents from the net, @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} requires an active TCP stack (@{b}AmiTCP@{ub}, @{b}Miami@{ub}, @{b}I-Net 225@{ub} or @{b}TermiteTCP@{ub}).

   The program searches for these enviroment variables:  @{b}USER@{ub} (user login), @{b}HOSTNAME@{ub} (local machine name) and @{b}REALNAME@{ub} (real first and last user name); it searches them in the @{b}ENV:@{ub} directory (or @{b}ENVARC:@{ub}).  These variables are usually updated by AmiTCP:  if they aren't correct, it's advisable to manually configure them.

@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "HTTPJ v2.00 - Installation"

   The installation process is limited to the copy of the executable in your preferred directory.  (I warmly suggest @{b}AmiTCP:Bin/@{ub}).

@EndNode

@Node "Usage" "HTTPJ v2.00 - Program usage"

   @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} may be directly used from shell or in a script, inside @{b}batch files@{ub} and @{b}ARexx scripts@{ub}.  The large number of @{"error codes" link "Errors" 0} permits a perfect management of any situation.

   @{b}Arguments@{ub} are passed using the Amiga format, they are the following:

@{b}    Url <Url>@{ub}

   This argument is required and specify the Internet document to download in the format of [http://]www.xxxxx.xxx[:port][/dir|file]. It can be a HTML page, an image or an archive. Default port is 80.

@{b}    To <FileName>@{ub}

   Name of the file on which the document will be saved.
   @{b}WARNING:@{ub} TO and MIRROR arguments are exclusive.

@{b}    Mirror <Path>@{ub}

   This argument activates multiple receipt mode. Required document and all their links until specified depth level will be saved to the specified path (a directory with the site name will be created).
   @{b}WARNING:@{ub} MIRROR and TO arguments are exclusive.

@{b}    Append@{ub}

   If this argument is specified, then the downloaded document will be appended to the destination file.

@{b}    Header@{ub}

   Adds an header to the document, indicating the URL it was downloaded from and date of download.

@{b}    Update@{ub}

   This argument can be used only if the document is saved on file. HTTPJ starts the download only if the remote file is newer than the local copy.

@{b}    Anonymous@{ub}

   Normally, HTTPJ asks for the user name and E-Mail in the HTTP Request. If these data are not to be sent, specify this argument.

@{b}    Proxy <Url>@{ub}

   Instead of directly calling the remote server, HTTPJ will use the specified proxy.  The proxy address is in the standard form [http://]www.xxxxx.xxx[:port]. Default port is 8080.

@{b}    NoCache@{ub}

   The utilization of this argument forces proxy to receive document from the server ignoring (if present) the local cached copy.

@{b}    NoImages@{ub}

   If this argument is specified then the program will not get backgrounds and images from the documents.

@{b}    NoFiles@{ub}

   If this argument is specified then the program will not get external files (archives, sounds or images) related to pages.

@{b}    MaxLocal <Level>@{ub}

   This argument specifies the maximum depth level to get documents when MIRROR argument is present.  Default value is 0 (gets only required document and related images).

@{b}    MaxHost <Level>@{ub}

   This argument specifies if and how many times it's possible to download documents located on different servers than the starting one.  Default value is 0 (gets only documents on the specified site).

@{b}    MirrorSite <address>@{ub}

   When MIRROR argument is specified to activate receipt of whole trees, @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} modifies links in HTML documents in order to always point them to received files. Specifying this argument, instead, it's possible to modify links in order to point them to the host site. In this way it's possible to manage a Mirror.

@{b}    MaxErrors <Level>@{ub}

   In multiple receipt mode, if an error happens while receiving a document, the request is tried two more times.  With this argument it's possible to change the maximum retries number.

@{b}    Buffer <KBytes>@{ub}

   HTTPJ tries to allocate a default buffer of 5k.  With this argument is possible to modify the buffer size, in Kbytes.

@{b}    LogFile <FileName>@{ub}

   If @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} is started from a script, it could be useful to have all operations and eventual errors written to a file, readable in a second time.
 
@{b}    Quiet@{ub}

   Specifying this argument, the program output (including error messages) will no longer display.


   Finally here are two explaining examples:

        HTTPJ www.amiga.de TO RAM:pippo.html UPDATE HEADER

   Gets document at address @{i}www.amiga.de@{ui} only if it has been updated and saves it to file @{i}RAM:pippo.html@{ui} adding an header.

        HTTPJ www.amiga.de MIRROR MIR: MAXLOCAL 3 MAXHOST 1

   Gets three local level documents from site @{i}www.amiga.de@{ui} exiting from this site if needed only for one level.  Files will be saved in directory @{i}MIR:www.amiga.de/@{ui} and all links will point here.

@EndNode

@Node "Support" "HTTPJ v2.00 - Program support"

            Program @{b}HTTPJ@{ub} has a support page at address

